g Kant, Spinoza, and Aristotle, as well as Fichte, Schelling, Hölderlin, and others).The commentator refrains from playing down (as many interpreters do today) those aspects of Hegel's thought that are less acceptable in our time, and abstains from mixing his own philosophical preferences with his reading of Hegel's text. His approach is faithful to the historical Hegel while reconstructing Hegel's ideas within their own context.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aConsciousness. 0aKnowledge, Theory of. 0aSpirit. 0aTruth. 7aPHILOSOPHY / General.2bisacsh1 aYovel, Yirmiyahu.40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781400826476zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781400826476423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781400826476/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK